nventor’s granddaughter","body":"In 1873 Kilbourn married Mary Adeline Douglas, granddaughter of the noted inventor William Douglas of Middletown, whose “Douglas Pump” was sold worldwide. Ironically, it was as a traveling salesman for the Douglas Pump company that Kilbourn first came west."},{"number":3,"category":"career","header":"He saw a savings bank swell by millions","body":"Before going west, Kilbourn rose from teller to treasurer of the Middletown Savings Bank across the 1870s, a period in which its deposits increased by several millions. He had begun his working life as purser aboard the steamship Liberty, running between New York and Havana."},{"number":4,"category":"character","header":"A churchman who built a mansion out West","body":"An elder and former treasurer of Pueblo’s First Presbyterian Church, Kilbourn built a prominent 1896 mansion where the family lived with domestic staff. His business reach extended to mining ventures across Nevada, California, and Colorado and a real-estate and loan agency."}],"career":[{"role":"Purser","organization":"Steamship Liberty (New York–Havana)","start_year":1864,"end_year":1865},{"role":"Clerk","organization":"Russell Manufacturing Co., Middletown","start_year":1865,"end_year":1870},{"role":"Teller, asst. secretary, treasurer","organization":"Middletown Savings Bank","start_year":1870,"end_year":1879},{"role":"Teller, assistant cashier","organization":"First National Bank, Pueblo","start_year":1881,"end_year":1884},{"role":"Receiver of Public Moneys","organization":"U.S. Land Office, Pueblo (appt. Pres. Cleveland)","start_year":1885,"end_year":1890},{"role":"Treasurer","organization":"Pueblo City Schools","start_year":1884,"end_year":null}],"education":[{"institution_name":"Daniel H. Chase’s Private School","relationship":"student","degree":"Preparatory"},{"institution_name":"Wesleyan University","relationship":"student","years":"to junior year","degree":"Left during junior year"}],"slug":"jonathan-burwell-kilbou